		<tr><td><div id=smtext><div class="canoe_hyperklix_text"><img src="/Images/invisible.gif" width=420 height=1><br>
      <p>
		        <table align=right width=250 cellpadding=5 cellspacing=0 border=0 class=microcell><tr><td>
<img src="/Living/2008/06/30/Mole.jpg" width=250><font color="#999999"><div id=xsmtext><img src="http://lifewise.canoe.ca/Images/invisible.gif" width=4 height=5><br><b>Neighbour Marc Beishon dryly jokes that they always expected William's head to suddenly poke out of their kitchen floor. (Comstock)</b></div></font>
</td></tr></table>
	    	


      <p>Over the decades, and under the noses of his neighbours, William Lyttle dug. </p>
<p>And dug. </p>
<p>And dug some more. </p>
<p>Until, one day, all that digging threatened to swallow a passing double-decker bus or his own weathered mansion above. </p>
<p>For 40 years, the retired English engineer quietly worked alone, expanding the basement at his family's Victoria era home, at 121 Mortimer Rd., in the London borough of Hackney. If reclusive William couldn't expand his social network above the soft clay base, he certainly did his best &mdash; with a small shovel and pulley-cart system &mdash; to carve out a subterranean retreat he could call his own. </p>
<p>But now, all that hard work has been sealed in concrete, and the chances of 77-year-old William digging out again are very slim indeed. </p>
<p>William, long known in his east-end community as the Mole Man, spent many waking hours creating a labyrinth of tunnels below his 20-room, four-storey inherited home. As the largely empty house above rotted away, William believed, through his endless excavations &mdash; which at one point partially ate away the sidewalk out front &mdash; were actually beautifying his inheritance. </p>
<p>Experts, called in by borough council, estimated the one little old man had managed to move 100 cubic meters of earth from beneath the roads and buildings close to his property. In all, he had reached out 18 metres beyond his basement, and only stopped digging deeper when he finally hit the water table. </p>
<p>Neighbour Marc Beishon dryly jokes that they always expected William's head to suddenly poke out of their kitchen floor. </p>
<p>While apparently shy of people, William did once allow a television crew to come inside to work on a show about extreme home improvements. </p>
<p>"This is how the pyramids were built - with blood, sweat and toil," he explained of his backbreaking work. </p>
<p>Pointing into the dark shadows of his 8-metre deep cavern, the house above held up with makeshift scaffolding, he explained with pride: "This is going to be the leisure centre." </p>
<p>But Mortimer Rd. never saw the completion of its underground leisure centre, or the point where William was finally happy with all that he had dug up. </p>
<p>Two years ago, local officials stepped in. And stepped down to pull him out of his hole. </p>
<p>They gave him an order to stay away from his home, circled it with sections of corrugated iron panels &mdash; which, at one point, he used to repair a leaking roof &mdash; and hauled away more than 33 tonnes of soil and garbage. They even had to remove trees from the property, because they had nothing under to cling to. Cars and a boat were found in holes in the garden. </p>
<p>Then, with foam concrete, they began filling in all William had cleared. </p>
<p>Recently, they sent him the bill for all his hard work &mdash; almost $600,000 (Can). </p>
<p>It's not expected he will ever be able to pay it and return to the place that he buried himself for 40 years. The property will likely be sold off to pay the bill. </p>
<p>"Mr. Lyttle has been prevented by court order from returning to the property since 2006, and the property has since been made safe...but not for an occupant," Hackney spokesman James Willsher tells Sun Media. </p>
<p>William is now living in a small hotel room the council arranged for him. </p>
<p>Still a recluse, and unavailable for an interview, he told the UK's Guardian in 2006: "I first tried to dig a wine cellar, and then the cellar doubled, and so on. </p>
<p>"But the idea that I dug tunnels under other people's houses is rubbish. I just have a big basement." </p>
<p>He added that people make too big a thing over a man who simply likes to dig. And dig. </p>
<p>As to why, that's an answer which has yet to surface. </p>
<p>"People are asking you what the big secret is &mdash; and you know what?&rdquo; he told a reporter two years ago. &ldquo;There isn't one."</p>      <br>
      
      <br></div></div></td></tr></table>
